<br>
So, you say, that's all good and all, but still, why Iraq?  Saddam was stupid enough to actually make two big mistakes.  He invaded Kuwait to avoid paying the Kuwatis for his massive debts to them from that Iran-Iraq War.  Yeah, the signals he got from the West didn't help here, but it was still a stupid solution.  When the world said &quot;OMFG, stop that!&quot; he decided to try the &quot;might makes right&quot; argument, which the world gladly took up and kicked his ass.  THEN, as part of a cease-fire agreement, he agreed to destroy and account for all his WMD.<br>
<br>
Which brings us to his second mistake:  He had already used his WMD both in the Iran-Iraq War and on his own people.  This, more than anything else, is why nobody wanted him and his Baathist Party (whose ideology is: &quot;Arabs are the superior race&quot;...sound familiar to you Europeans?) to control all that oil.  Everybody agrees that having nukes and other WMD requires reasonable leadership...ask yourself if you want Saddam to have WMD.  Now add in 12 years of evasion, denials, and deceit.  He even kicked out the weapon inspectors in 1998!  Ask yourself what Clinton would have done if he hadn't been playing with cigars with White House interns.  Remember how people thought his bombing strikes then were just to get everybody to forget about that blue Gap dress?<br>
<br>
What boggles my mind is that for 12 years, Saddam has made a mockery of virtually all his agreements with the UN and the Coalition simply because he didn't want to seem weak and defeated.  Remember, before Saddam got all glassy-eyed conqueror-delusional, Iraq was the most affluent and advanced of all the Middle East.  After Lebabon fell to shit, and Beirut was no longer the &quot;Paris of the Mideast&quot;, that honor fell on Baghdad.  Then sanctions happened and Saddam, once again, gave his people the shaft and let them get practically medieval as the Iraqui economy was gutted.  Even Oil for Food failed, as Saddam used much of that money for rebuilding his military and making palaces.  In fact, he even used the process of awarding contracts for rebuilding Iraq once santions were lifted to undermine the sanctions.  No company that was based in or had offices in any country that supported sanctions was awarded a contract, period.  Curiously, that means that a lot of Russian, German, French, and even Canadian companies got those contracts, while not a single American or British company did...one of those things that make you go &quot;hmmm&quot;. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mrbanderas>Mr Banderas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 233<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/27/03 12:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2.topic&index=53>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wrong Protest at the Wrong Time</span><hr size=1> I support the war, I just laughed at our government's excuse for it.<br>
